{"id":"1810.02627","submitter":"Alexander Mozeika","authors":"Alexander Mozeika and Anthony CC Coolen","title":"Replica analysis of Bayesian data clustering","comments":"Most recent version with extended Introduction and additional Figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We use statistical mechanics to study model-based Bayesian data clustering.\nIn this approach, each partition of the data into clusters is regarded as a\nmicroscopic system state, the negative data log-likelihood gives the energy of\neach state, and the data set realisation acts as disorder. Optimal clustering\ncorresponds to the ground state of the system, and is hence obtained from the\nfree energy via a low `temperature' limit. We assume that for large sample\nsizes the free energy density is self-averaging, and we use the replica method\nto compute the asymptotic free energy density. The main order parameter in the\nresulting (replica symmetric) theory, the distribution of the data over the\nclusters, satisfies a self-consistent equation which can be solved by a\npopulation dynamics algorithm. From this order parameter one computes the\naverage free energy, and all relevant macroscopic characteristics of the\nproblem. The theory describes numerical experiments perfectly, and gives a\nsignificant improvement over the mean-field theory that was used to study this\nmodel in past.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 5 Oct 2018 11:53:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 19 Dec 2018 23:52:25 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 18 Nov 2019 09:26:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-19"}
